WEBVTT

1
00:00:05.400 --> 00:00:08.840
Thank you everyone. My name is Justin Shapiro, and I'm here representing Circle

2
00:00:08.960 --> 00:00:12.600
Pharma. We are a biotech drug discovery company focused on

3
00:00:12.620 --> 00:00:16.060
developing orally bioavailable macrocycles which can target and

4
00:00:16.101 --> 00:00:18.620
disrupt intracellular protein-protein interactions.

5
00:00:19.800 --> 00:00:23.360
Quick plugs for the plenary clinical session tomorrow and the new drugs on the

6
00:00:23.400 --> 00:00:25.840
horizon session the day after. Please go check those out.

7
00:00:26.800 --> 00:00:29.099
But in the meantime, I have a bit of a discovery story for you.

8
00:00:30.420 --> 00:00:34.120
So, no one in this audience needs to be told that peptide therapeutics are having a

9
00:00:34.140 --> 00:00:37.980
little bit of a moment. Specifically, the subset of macrocyclic

10
00:00:38.040 --> 00:00:42.020
peptides have had a couple of really high-profile successes against

11
00:00:42.040 --> 00:00:43.600
very challenging targets recently.

12
00:00:44.430 --> 00:00:48.320
And this has highlighted the ability of this exciting modality to get the

13
00:00:48.380 --> 00:00:52.200
kinds of pharmacokinetic parameters and manufacturability of small

14
00:00:52.280 --> 00:00:56.140
molecules balanced with the kinds of potency and selectivity that you

15
00:00:56.180 --> 00:00:58.260
can typically only get out of biologics.

16
00:01:00.180 --> 00:01:03.560
But if we take a broad view of the field, some remaining obstacles emerge.

17
00:01:04.420 --> 00:01:08.400
The space can be broadly divided along two axes, with the route of administration

18
00:01:08.440 --> 00:01:12.160
shown along the top and the location of the molecular target shown along the

19
00:01:12.200 --> 00:01:12.540
side.

20
00:01:14.140 --> 00:01:17.780
For compounds with extracellular targets, many of them rely on a number of

21
00:01:17.880 --> 00:01:21.160
charged residues to tightly interact with the protein of interest,

22
00:01:21.980 --> 00:01:25.560
and therefore the development of a more neutral and potentially more orally

23
00:01:25.600 --> 00:01:29.280
bioavailable analog with sufficient potency is simply going to be out of the

24
00:01:29.320 --> 00:01:29.680
question.

25
00:01:31.980 --> 00:01:35.900
If you begin to carve away charge, you can gain access to the interior of the cell,

26
00:01:36.680 --> 00:01:40.580
but many compounds with intracellular targets still do not have intrinsic

27
00:01:40.680 --> 00:01:44.640
oral bioavailability. They cannot cross the gut wall, and therefore they

28
00:01:44.680 --> 00:01:47.620
must be administered via injection, putting them in the bottom left.

29
00:01:49.800 --> 00:01:53.560
If you have exquisite potency for an extracellular target and you're not too

30
00:01:53.640 --> 00:01:57.260
bogged down by charge, you can hope for oral dosing, as in the case of

31
00:01:57.300 --> 00:02:00.840
Merck's PCSK9 inhibitors and the recently unveiled

32
00:02:01.180 --> 00:02:02.680
IL-23 oral inhibitor.

33
00:02:04.080 --> 00:02:07.260
Compounds in this upper right-hand box do not tend to have intrinsic oral

34
00:02:07.320 --> 00:02:08.150
bioavailability,

35
00:02:09.461 --> 00:02:13.070
but with the help of an enabling formulation, enough of them can get forced

36
00:02:13.180 --> 00:02:17.080
past the gut wall that they can find and inhibit their extracellular target

37
00:02:17.120 --> 00:02:19.840
without ever having to cross a membrane all by themselves.

38
00:02:22.020 --> 00:02:25.920
There are macrocyclic peptides which both have intrinsic oral bioavailability

39
00:02:25.940 --> 00:02:29.640
and are able to passively permeate a cell membrane to find and

40
00:02:29.700 --> 00:02:31.420
inhibit their intracellular targets.

41
00:02:32.440 --> 00:02:36.180
But case studies are few and far between, and importantly, they have largely

42
00:02:36.280 --> 00:02:39.660
focused to date on targets which can be drugged via non-peptide

43
00:02:39.740 --> 00:02:41.500
modalities such as RAS.

44
00:02:42.820 --> 00:02:46.640
So Circle Pharma aims to populate this bottom right-hand box with new targets that

45
00:02:46.720 --> 00:02:50.269
have novel mechanisms of action which are currently considered undruggable.

46
00:02:52.980 --> 00:02:55.810
I think this audience is probably familiar with the cell cycle, but very briefly,

47
00:02:56.480 --> 00:03:00.340
it is the process by which a cell grows, duplicates DNA, and divides

48
00:03:00.380 --> 00:03:04.340
in two. And in a healthy cell, the orderly transition between the

49
00:03:04.380 --> 00:03:08.260
phases of the cell cycle is a tightly regulated process controlled

50
00:03:08.300 --> 00:03:12.160
by cyclin-dependent kinase phosphorylation events, and those are

51
00:03:12.200 --> 00:03:15.040
regulated even further by their cognate cyclins.

52
00:03:17.080 --> 00:03:18.740
The cyclin serves two key functions here.

53
00:03:19.200 --> 00:03:23.120
The first is to cause a conformational shift in the CDK, which turns on its

54
00:03:23.180 --> 00:03:24.120
catalytic activity,

55
00:03:25.010 --> 00:03:28.410
and the second is to recruit regulatory peptides through protein-protein

56
00:03:28.440 --> 00:03:31.109
interactions with a hotspot on the cyclin surface.

57
00:03:32.640 --> 00:03:36.020
Once localized to the complex, the substrate can wrap itself around and the

58
00:03:36.040 --> 00:03:39.680
business end can get phosphorylated, and then the downstream regulatory

59
00:03:39.760 --> 00:03:40.880
cascade can proceed.

60
00:03:42.180 --> 00:03:45.780
So in cancer cells, unmitigated progression through this cell cycle leads to

61
00:03:45.840 --> 00:03:49.820
uncontrolled cell growth, and so strategies for inhibiting the cell cycle have

62
00:03:49.840 --> 00:03:53.760
been of interest to the industry for decades, most clearly exemplified

63
00:03:53.840 --> 00:03:57.640
by clinically approved CDK4/6 inhibitors targeting the kinase-active

64
00:03:57.720 --> 00:03:58.000
site.

65
00:03:59.500 --> 00:04:03.460
But that approach has drawbacks. High structural homology between kinase-active

66
00:04:03.500 --> 00:04:07.220
sites can lead to off-target toxicity, and resistance development is a known

67
00:04:07.380 --> 00:04:11.140
concern. So alternative strategies for modulating the cell

68
00:04:11.200 --> 00:04:12.900
cycle are still highly attractive.

69
00:04:15.240 --> 00:04:18.620
One way of going about this is by targeting the substrate recruitment site on the

70
00:04:18.661 --> 00:04:19.541
surface of the cyclin.

71
00:04:20.700 --> 00:04:24.519
Shown here is the RXL binding site of cyclin A, so called

72
00:04:24.540 --> 00:04:28.400
because it recognizes a conserved sequence found across many cyclin

73
00:04:28.500 --> 00:04:28.969
substrates.

74
00:04:30.100 --> 00:04:34.080
And a member of our scientific advisory board, Bill Kaelin, was the first to

75
00:04:34.120 --> 00:04:38.020
demonstrate the potential for synthetic lethality in specific

76
00:04:38.060 --> 00:04:41.520
kinds of cancer cells with certain genetic dysregulations if you

77
00:04:41.560 --> 00:04:44.560
inhibit the RXL binding pocket of the cyclins.

78
00:04:47.500 --> 00:04:51.480
From the crystal structure of a natural substrate in the RXL binding site of cyclin

79
00:04:51.700 --> 00:04:55.220
A, McInnes and coworkers identified intramolecular

80
00:04:55.300 --> 00:04:59.000
hydrogen bonds between a side chain amide and a backbone amide

81
00:04:59.060 --> 00:05:01.710
that reinforce the active conformation of the substrate,

82
00:05:02.720 --> 00:05:06.460
and they hypothesized that they could emulate this effect by linking that

83
00:05:06.500 --> 00:05:09.040
side chain to the C-terminus of a substrate mimic,

84
00:05:10.040 --> 00:05:14.000
leading them to compound one, which has superior biochemical potency

85
00:05:14.010 --> 00:05:16.740
compared to the equivalent length linear substrate

86
00:05:16.780 --> 00:05:20.680
fragment. But despite that promising initial result,

87
00:05:21.400 --> 00:05:24.820
none of the groups that have worked on this target since have been able to develop

88
00:05:25.100 --> 00:05:26.840
cellularly active inhibitors.

89
00:05:27.640 --> 00:05:31.600
This is because they rely on a conserved charged arginine residue

90
00:05:31.660 --> 00:05:33.430
as a necessary part of the pharmacophore,

91
00:05:34.340 --> 00:05:38.220
so any compound with interesting levels of biochemical activity is not able to

92
00:05:38.300 --> 00:05:39.790
passively permeate a membrane.

93
00:05:40.960 --> 00:05:44.640
Circle Pharma saw this as a perfect opportunity to deploy its discovery

94
00:05:44.720 --> 00:05:48.180
platform to go from this weak biochemical hit with no permeability

95
00:05:48.780 --> 00:05:51.620
to a cellularly potent permeable cyclin inhibitor.

96
00:05:52.680 --> 00:05:56.480
And to enable this, a computational binding model was developed in which

97
00:05:56.540 --> 00:06:00.520
three key interactions were identified, which were to be retained and

98
00:06:00.720 --> 00:06:04.468
optimized throughout the discovery campaign.One,

99
00:06:05.158 --> 00:06:09.108
a central beta strand forms a hydrogen bonding network with the protein target.

100
00:06:10.248 --> 00:06:14.108
Two, there are two lipophilic residues in the macrocycle which settle

101
00:06:14.148 --> 00:06:15.868
into a deep hydrophobic patch.

102
00:06:17.008 --> 00:06:20.608
And three, a beta turn near the N-terminus of the tail

103
00:06:21.108 --> 00:06:23.188
settles into a shallow secondary pocket.

104
00:06:26.268 --> 00:06:29.938
So we begin with this literature compound with absolutely abysmal properties,

105
00:06:30.168 --> 00:06:34.018
and although we do have measurable biochemical activity in our fluorescence

106
00:06:34.108 --> 00:06:36.048
polarization assay for cyclin A,

107
00:06:37.128 --> 00:06:40.078
the MDCK permeability is below the limit of quantitation.

108
00:06:42.308 --> 00:06:45.828
Through an iterative process of computationally driven designs and solid phase

109
00:06:45.888 --> 00:06:49.768
peptide synthesis, the first compound in the history of this target

110
00:06:49.788 --> 00:06:53.528
was identified that has confirmed anti-proliferative cellular

111
00:06:53.628 --> 00:06:57.428
activity against a small cell lung cancer line that has the

112
00:06:57.468 --> 00:07:01.368
exact kinds of genetic dysregulations that were predicted in Bill Kaelin's original

113
00:07:01.448 --> 00:07:02.108
hypothesis.

114
00:07:04.888 --> 00:07:08.768
Building on this momentum, we introduced turn-inducing motifs into both the

115
00:07:08.788 --> 00:07:12.688
macrocycle and into the peptide tail to reinforce the active

116
00:07:12.708 --> 00:07:16.538
conformation of the substrate. And when combined with optimized

117
00:07:16.568 --> 00:07:20.488
hydrophobic contacts, as well as just generally pumping up the lipophilicity of

118
00:07:20.528 --> 00:07:21.098
the molecule,

119
00:07:21.898 --> 00:07:25.748
we arrive at compound three, which has double-digit nanomolar cellular potency

120
00:07:25.888 --> 00:07:28.188
and significantly improved MDCK.

121
00:07:29.148 --> 00:07:31.868
And we were excited enough about this compound that we wanted to profile it

122
00:07:31.908 --> 00:07:32.148
further.

123
00:07:33.608 --> 00:07:36.668
And as you can see, we have come a long way from our literature starting point.

124
00:07:38.108 --> 00:07:41.988
We have single-digit nanomolar biophysical affinity for cyclins A

125
00:07:42.128 --> 00:07:46.028
and B with selectivity over cyclin E, and we will return to

126
00:07:46.068 --> 00:07:47.588
the subject of the different cyclins later.

127
00:07:48.808 --> 00:07:52.508
But this leads to potent inhibition of small cell lung cancer lines with no

128
00:07:52.548 --> 00:07:54.718
effect on healthy human fibroblasts.

129
00:07:56.038 --> 00:07:59.928
Our properties and our in vitro DMPK are maybe not quite where we want them just

130
00:08:00.068 --> 00:08:03.168
yet, but we're at least within striking distance of something a little bit more

131
00:08:03.188 --> 00:08:03.658
drug-like.

132
00:08:04.948 --> 00:08:08.428
And we were delighted to see that when we put this compound into a

133
00:08:08.488 --> 00:08:10.618
CDX mouse model of small cell lung cancer,

134
00:08:11.568 --> 00:08:14.948
we achieved tumor regression at 100 mgs per kg QD via

135
00:08:14.988 --> 00:08:17.828
intraperitoneal dosing with no body weight loss.

136
00:08:18.688 --> 00:08:18.788
So,

137
00:08:19.668 --> 00:08:23.628
huge milestone for us. We have connected the in vitro mechanism of action to

138
00:08:23.648 --> 00:08:25.568
an in vivo phenotypic response.

139
00:08:26.728 --> 00:08:30.188
This hit-to-lead campaign was published in the "Journal of Medicinal Chemistry" so

140
00:08:30.288 --> 00:08:33.937
please go give that a read if you'd like to learn more about this arm of the

141
00:08:34.009 --> 00:08:34.468
program.

142
00:08:35.629 --> 00:08:39.578
That said, as big of an achievement as this was, the compound does not

143
00:08:39.648 --> 00:08:43.408
have oral bioavailability, which we need to advance this compound into the

144
00:08:43.448 --> 00:08:45.868
clinic. So we still have some work to do.

145
00:08:48.668 --> 00:08:52.608
Our primary strategy for optimizing compound three was to reduce its peptidic

146
00:08:52.648 --> 00:08:53.048
character.

147
00:08:53.928 --> 00:08:57.428
We see that by methylating the lariat amide leading up to the bridging

148
00:08:57.508 --> 00:09:01.408
residue, along with a couple of other minor structural modifications, leads

149
00:09:01.468 --> 00:09:05.348
us to compound four, which is equipotent in cellular assay but has

150
00:09:05.408 --> 00:09:07.108
modestly improved MDCK.

151
00:09:08.708 --> 00:09:12.608
By itself, nothing to write home about, but we thought to ourselves, what if

152
00:09:12.648 --> 00:09:14.687
we took this modification even further?

153
00:09:15.768 --> 00:09:19.458
What if instead of just methylating that amide, we get rid of it altogether and

154
00:09:19.528 --> 00:09:23.448
replace the bridging residue with an alkyl chain in a new scaffold

155
00:09:23.488 --> 00:09:25.808
that we dub our long lariat series.

156
00:09:26.948 --> 00:09:30.848
In this particular example, compound five, we have also methylated the long lariat,

157
00:09:31.328 --> 00:09:35.008
and that leads us to a compound with improved cellular activity and further

158
00:09:35.108 --> 00:09:36.468
improved MDCK.

159
00:09:37.488 --> 00:09:41.348
So we think we're onto something at this stage, but our other in

160
00:09:41.388 --> 00:09:44.688
vitro DMPK parameters are still not quite where we want them.

161
00:09:45.748 --> 00:09:49.528
Our solubility is very low, and our plasma protein binding is very

162
00:09:49.608 --> 00:09:53.408
high, which is going to lead to very low free drug fractions in

163
00:09:53.468 --> 00:09:56.328
vivo, which is going to prevent us from seeing efficacy.

164
00:09:58.928 --> 00:10:02.448
But by systematically modifying the phenylalanine residue, we arrive at

165
00:10:02.488 --> 00:10:05.728
compound six, and now we've really gotten somewhere.

166
00:10:05.738 --> 00:10:09.518
Cellular activity and MDCK have once again been improved, and

167
00:10:09.568 --> 00:10:13.428
now our Ksol and our plasma protein binding are in a range where we

168
00:10:13.448 --> 00:10:17.268
feel comfortable advancing this compound into further evaluations in

169
00:10:17.348 --> 00:10:21.048
preparation for a potential in vivo PO efficacy study.

170
00:10:23.788 --> 00:10:27.488
Compound six has low single-digit nanomolar biophysical affinity for

171
00:10:27.528 --> 00:10:31.008
cyclins A and B with moderate selectivity against cyclin E,

172
00:10:31.968 --> 00:10:35.108
and this leads to potent inhibition in multiple small cell lung cancer

173
00:10:35.198 --> 00:10:38.788
lines with no effect, once again, on healthy human fibroblasts.

174
00:10:40.308 --> 00:10:43.868
Properties in in vitro DMPK have been further improved.

175
00:10:43.948 --> 00:10:47.748
In vivo, we see dose proportionality going from 30 to 100

176
00:10:47.768 --> 00:10:51.548
mgs per kg PO in the mouse, and that's hovering at around 30%

177
00:10:51.768 --> 00:10:51.848
F.

178
00:10:53.148 --> 00:10:57.068
And although I'm not showing it today, we have clean profiles across a number of in

179
00:10:57.108 --> 00:10:58.928
vitro safety pharmacology panels.

180
00:10:59.508 --> 00:11:03.408
All of this supports the nomination of compound six to PO oral

181
00:11:03.448 --> 00:11:03.868
efficacy.

182
00:11:06.808 --> 00:11:10.288
So we put this compound into two CDX mouse models of small cell lung

183
00:11:10.328 --> 00:11:12.888
cancer. I will not belabor the details here.

184
00:11:12.928 --> 00:11:15.108
I'm just going to give you the two key takeaways.

185
00:11:15.848 --> 00:11:19.648
One, compound is well-tolerated, as seen in the central body weight

186
00:11:19.728 --> 00:11:20.088
curves.

187
00:11:21.348 --> 00:11:24.788
And two, as we begin to dose up the compound in the mouse,

188
00:11:25.268 --> 00:11:28.948
we start to see robust tumor regressions at the dosing levels, which can

189
00:11:28.988 --> 00:11:32.948
achieve a free Cmax in excess of the GI50, which

190
00:11:32.988 --> 00:11:34.228
is what you're seeing on the right.

191
00:11:34.908 --> 00:11:38.468
And this reinforces the importance of keeping a close eye on that plasma protein

192
00:11:38.548 --> 00:11:42.528
binding and using in vivo free drug fraction as a driving force

193
00:11:42.548 --> 00:11:43.328
for optimization.

194
00:11:45.128 --> 00:11:48.838
We see similar results in patient-derived xenograft models of triple-negative

195
00:11:48.948 --> 00:11:49.488
breast cancer.

196
00:11:50.548 --> 00:11:54.088
This lead optimization portion of the program was also published in "J Med Chem,"

197
00:11:54.168 --> 00:11:58.138
so go give that a read. And although this molecule was not selected

198
00:11:58.138 --> 00:12:01.488
to advance into the clinic, it was an important tool

199
00:12:01.548 --> 00:12:05.338
compound and the marquee molecule of a publication that we put into

200
00:12:05.338 --> 00:12:08.550
"Nature."Detailing the underlying mechanistic

201
00:12:08.620 --> 00:12:12.540
biology of how neither cyclin A inhibition alone nor cyclin

202
00:12:12.580 --> 00:12:16.200
B inhibition alone is sufficient to drive apoptosis.

203
00:12:16.240 --> 00:12:17.720
You really do need to have both.

204
00:12:19.360 --> 00:12:22.840
We also looked at why certain types of cancer cells were susceptible to our

205
00:12:22.880 --> 00:12:23.940
mechanism over others.

206
00:12:24.780 --> 00:12:28.240
As a part of that publication, we put together this little video, and I would like

207
00:12:28.300 --> 00:12:29.500
to show it to you right now.

208
00:12:31.160 --> 00:12:34.760
Cercul Pharma is developing CID078, a

209
00:12:34.820 --> 00:12:38.769
first-in-class macrocyclic cyclin inhibitor designed to disrupt

210
00:12:38.799 --> 00:12:42.430
the cell cycle of malignant cells that have aberrant E2F activity.

211
00:12:44.600 --> 00:12:48.260
CID078 binds to a previously undruggable

212
00:12:48.269 --> 00:12:52.210
hydrophobic patch on each of the cyclin A CDK2 and

213
00:12:52.240 --> 00:12:56.070
cyclin B CDK1 complexes, influencing interactions with

214
00:12:56.080 --> 00:12:59.540
substrates and regulators while sparing the kinase binding site.

215
00:13:01.720 --> 00:13:05.240
Normally, the cyclin A CDK2 complex regulates proper

216
00:13:05.260 --> 00:13:08.620
completion of the S phase of the cell cycle by inactivating

217
00:13:08.680 --> 00:13:09.260
E2F.

218
00:13:11.860 --> 00:13:14.200
In tumor cells with aberrant E2F activity,

219
00:13:14.560 --> 00:13:18.320
CID078 prevents this complex from turning E2F

220
00:13:18.460 --> 00:13:21.680
off, leading to DNA damage and replication stress.

221
00:13:23.620 --> 00:13:26.820
Subsequently, during the G2 and M phases of the cell cycle,

222
00:13:27.220 --> 00:13:30.160
CID078 also disrupts cyclin B

223
00:13:30.180 --> 00:13:33.580
downregulation by MYT1, resulting in sustained

224
00:13:33.640 --> 00:13:37.500
activity of the cyclin B CDK1 complex, forcing the

225
00:13:37.540 --> 00:13:40.240
tumor cells into mitotic division.

226
00:13:40.270 --> 00:13:44.240
These two effects, replication stress with DNA damage and forced

227
00:13:44.260 --> 00:13:48.220
transition into the division phase, combine to produce mitotic catastrophe

228
00:13:48.230 --> 00:13:52.160
and apoptosis, resulting in the death of the tumor cells.

229
00:13:56.460 --> 00:14:00.220
So if you'd like to learn more about that biology, please go give that paper a read

230
00:14:00.300 --> 00:14:02.720
and check out our talks tomorrow and the day after.

231
00:14:03.100 --> 00:14:06.400
There's some really fascinating underlying mechanistic biology behind this

232
00:14:06.460 --> 00:14:06.860
compound.

233
00:14:09.480 --> 00:14:12.660
With the remainder of my time, I would like to tell you about Cercul's second

234
00:14:12.780 --> 00:14:15.939
development program, which was born out of our deep knowledge of cyclin

235
00:14:15.960 --> 00:14:18.920
biology, and that one is focused on cyclin D1.

236
00:14:20.320 --> 00:14:24.000
This particular cyclin mediates progression through the G1 phase of the cell

237
00:14:24.020 --> 00:14:26.780
cycle by pairing with either CDK4 or

238
00:14:26.860 --> 00:14:30.640
CDK6 to phosphorylate the retinoblastoma or

239
00:14:30.900 --> 00:14:31.660
Rb protein.

240
00:14:33.060 --> 00:14:37.020
Cyclin D1 dysregulation is a hallmark of many cancer subtypes, including

241
00:14:37.030 --> 00:14:39.620
heme and ER positive breast malignancies.

242
00:14:40.460 --> 00:14:44.169
I mentioned earlier that resistance development to CDK inhibitors is a

243
00:14:44.200 --> 00:14:45.060
known concern.

244
00:14:46.220 --> 00:14:49.890
