253
00:15:24.480 --> 00:15:28.440
Well, different cell types utilize different isoforms of cyclin

254
00:15:28.520 --> 00:15:30.009
D to drive G1 progression.

255
00:15:31.160 --> 00:15:34.920
Inside of ER-positive breast cancer cells, and in fact, many other cancer cell

256
00:15:34.980 --> 00:15:38.940
types, they are primarily relying on cyclin D1 paired with

257
00:15:39.000 --> 00:15:41.300
either CDK4 or CDK6,

258
00:15:42.200 --> 00:15:46.080
whereas in heme stem cells, as well as many other types of healthy human cells,

259
00:15:46.600 --> 00:15:50.200
they are primarily relying on the D3 CDK6 complex.

260
00:15:52.820 --> 00:15:56.440
CDK4/6 inhibitors are incredibly effective at shutting down Rb

261
00:15:56.560 --> 00:16:00.520
phosphorylation inside of the tumor compartment, but they also do so

262
00:16:00.580 --> 00:16:04.320
in the heme stem cells, which leads to dose-limiting on-target

263
00:16:04.380 --> 00:16:07.680
toxicity, primarily in the form of heme adverse events.

264
00:16:10.280 --> 00:16:14.110
Next generation CDK4 selective inhibitors attempt to circumvent this

265
00:16:14.120 --> 00:16:17.840
problem by only shutting down the D1 CDK4

266
00:16:17.850 --> 00:16:18.380
complex.

267
00:16:19.560 --> 00:16:23.389
Indeed, this does lead to lower toxicity, but it also

268
00:16:23.420 --> 00:16:26.910
gives the possibility that upregulated CDK6 can

269
00:16:26.980 --> 00:16:30.710
compensate for the inactivated complex, leading to G1 escape.

270
00:16:33.360 --> 00:16:37.170
Isoform selective cyclin D1 inhibitors offer the potential for the best of both

271
00:16:37.200 --> 00:16:40.680
worlds. If you can totally shut down both pathways of Rb

272
00:16:40.800 --> 00:16:44.600
phosphorylation inside of the tumor compartment, but you leave the heme stem cells

273
00:16:44.649 --> 00:16:48.140
alone, this could give you an improved therapeutic index.

274
00:16:48.200 --> 00:16:52.040
